  "experiments_summary": "The study evaluated three open-source generative models (REINVENT, MolMIM, and Mol-AIR) for generating porous carbon materials (Covalent Triazine Frameworks) for supercapacitors. Models were tested across 30 different configurations combining various transfer learning strategies: pre-training on ChEMBL datasets (versions 25, 29, 35) and ZINC-15, fine-tuning on a curated dataset of 103 CTF structures (substrates and lattice nodes), and reinforcement learning with custom reward functions. The reward functions incorporated expert-defined criteria including molecular flatness (RMSE from plane fitting), symmetry (Continuous Symmetry Measure for C2/C3/C4 groups), conjugation (electron transfer paths between nitrogen atoms), steric hindrance (nitrogen atom distances <4.1Å), and pattern matching (SMARTS-based). Each configuration was sampled 10 times (10,000 molecules for REINVENT/Mol-AIR, 100 per training instance for MolMIM) to compute mean and standard deviation of six metrics: validity, uniqueness, internal diversity (Tanimoto similarity-based), Fréchet ChemNet Distance, novelty, and percentage passing expert filters. Experiments addressed policy collapse in REINVENT by adjusting RL parameters (learning rate 0.00005, sigma 256, diversity filter changes). Training was conducted on NVIDIA A100 GPU with 72-hour time limits, using PyTorch 2.5.1, RDKit 2025.3.5, and model-specific environments. Data splits were 70/20/10 for pre-training and 80/20 for fine-tuning, with substrate-lattice node pairs kept together in splits."
